<br>
Under the NToV agreement, NToV has been interpreted to mean as Aary and beyond. I recall having seen it referred to as such many times. The agreement specifically references Sontalak, Ikitiar, Eashen as not being part of the rotation because they are before you get to Aaryonar. Ring of Vulak (RoV) is beyond Aaryonar. In order to do RoV, you have to clear the Lords and Ladies so they will not be summoned to aid during the fight. That makes clearing NToV an integral part of doing RoV successfully. <br>
<br>
There is no precedent that it is not part of the rotation. In fact, every time ToN has wanted to do RoV during Isengard's week, they asked first whether we were going to do it. The first time this happened, Tose asked the for the conversation to be logged so that he had a record that Isengard said it was fine for ToN to do RoV during our week. Every time after that, although I am unsure if the conversation was logged, we were still asked first. So to us, the fact that the person who led the rotation (via his raid leader) came to us and asked if it was okay for them to do RoV during our rotation week, implies that it would be not okay for them to do it without asking. This strengthened the idea to us that RoV was in fact part of the rotation and during our week, as long as we held to all other rotation rules, we would have no competition for it.<br>
<br>
Summary: <br>
(Aary and beyond = NToV) + (RoV = Beyond Aary) = RoV is covered under the rotation agreement. <br>
<br>
<br>
I like the NToV rotation agreement. Our guild likes it. The agreement succeeds or fails based on a mutual respect and understanding of the guilds on the server. Guilds that leave the rotation understand that by doing so, they cannot go back (&quot;gifting&quot; issue addressed below). Granted, most that leave don't want to go back because they have bigger fish to fry. Guilds that leave the rotation should understand that by doing so, they cannot go back unless they wish to rejoin the rotation. Being out of the rotation has as much responsibility as being in it.<br>
<br>
Guilds that want into the rotation understand that they need to work with a rotation guild to be allowed a chance to kill Aaryonar to prove they are ready. This starts them out in a cooperative relationship with at least one guild in the rotation and hopefully that relationship gets built upon. <br>
<br>
<br>
So if RoV is part of the NToV rotation, which Isengard believes it is: <br>
<br>
How long does a rotation guild have during their rotation week to complete Vulak ?  The same amount of time as they have to kill any other dragon there.  As long as Aary is killed within 24 hours and as long as you don't leave the zone with mobs up for more than 48 hours, NToV is yours during your week. It doesn't matter if you spend 5 straight nights wiping to it as long as you are there trying. If you go raid something else, or if you leave for 48 hours, then its FFA and anyone can go in. Those are the same rules as the rest of NToV.  <br>
<br>
&quot;Gifting&quot; RoV to another guild - this is where I always get fuzzy because truthfully, gifting doesn't bother us. As long as we are part of the rotation, we get NToV every 5 weeks or so. We don't much care what happens there in the other 4. If Inconceivable wants to let another guild use their week, who cares. All we care about is what happens during the week Isengard is there. <br>
<br>
No guild in the rotation has ever complained to us when ToN did RoV during our week in the past, so I do not see that it should ever be a problem in the future. That to me, is how it should be. If another guild takes the initiative to approach us and say &quot;Are you doing RoV this week?&quot; and we aren't, then why should anyone get their panties all in a bunch about 'gifting' ?  There are just more important things to worry about than that. <br>
<br>
Isengard will always go through the procedure of asking the current Rotation Guild if RoV is FFA in the event that it isnt our week. We believe the NTOV Rotation to be a SERVER wide agreement, not just between a few guilds.<br>
<br>
<br>
So a final summary of Isengard's stance here: <br>
<br>
Ring of Vulak is part of the NToV agreement. To be able to uphold the spirit of the NToV agreement, you cannot do RoV without checking with the rotation guild in NToV that week. It is Isengard's stance that it does not care if a guild passes on RoV and lets another guild do it. Further it is our stance if you raid another mob or leave for 48 hours with stuff up, RoV becomes FFA along with the rest of NToV.  <br>
<br>
We completely understand that the NToV agreement is only as strong as server support of it. Our stance is that the rotation is a server wide agreement (not just between a few guilds) meaning that there are guilds INSIDE NToV (in the rotation) and there are guilds OUTSIDE NToV (not in the rotation). Those outside have as much responsibility to follow the agreement as those inside; meaning they must not violate any guild's rotation week because they're bored or whatever, without asking first whether it is ok. <br>
<br>
Thus far, it has the server support and we would not like to see that change. Our time in NToV is coming to an end soon but we hope to see the rotation agreement stand strong because it is one of the few positive examples of guild interaction left on the server.  <p><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=255219" target="top">Mistress Azoicia Deviante</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
